{
  "doc_id": "31608",
  "text": "Divergent thinking has a long tradition in the creativity literature. Guilford (1950) introduced the construct and advanced a mode of assessment that remains widely used in modern research [CITATION_1] . The most common Contents lists available at ScienceDirect journal homepage: www.elsevier.com/locate/neuropsychologia divergent thinking assessment is the alternate uses task, which involves producing novel uses for common objects (e.g., a brick). A central virtue of such tasks is their predictive power: a longitudinal study of divergent thinking ability in school-aged children, for example, found that the top performers eventually lead highly successful careers in the arts and sciences [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Other work has since shown that divergent thinking predicts both the quantity of self-reported creative achievements ) and the quality of expert-rated creative performances [CITATION_4] .",
